This post is all about one of the trickiest parts of the ChatGPT interface:=
 Custom Instructions.=20
People think this is easy, and I find they often fill in LOTS of stuff abou=
t their lives, their personal preferences, the company=E2=80=99s priorities=
=E2=80=94stuff that ends up confusing and tricking the model into giving un=
helpful responses to day-to-day work.
The answer isn=E2=80=99t to avoid Custom Instructions (CI), it=E2=80=99s to=
 learn what they are for, where they slot in the prompt priority stack (the=
re is one!), and to learn how to write an excellent Custom Instruction that=
 actually simplifies your life.=20
And yes, this post includes lots of examples of real CI prompts, a punch li=
st to get started, and pitfalls to avoid. As a bonus, I also call out where=
 to use Custom GPTs vs Custom Instructions, since those are frequently conf=
used.=20
Net net, this should give you an actual guidepost to what to do with those =
mysterious CI boxes.
Subscribers get all these posts!
Custom Instructions - oh my oh my
You=E2=80=99re about to spend a few minutes learning when (and when not) to=
 touch the =E2=80=9CCustom Instructions=E2=80=9D panel=E2=80=94the two 1500=
-character boxes that quietly shape every ChatGPT reply you get. This guide=
 is for three overlapping groups:
Explorers who hop between recipe tweaks and grant proposals and wonder why =
the assistant sometimes answers like a corporate intern.
Power-users who live in the prompt window drafting PRDs, marketing copy, or=
 customer emails and crave voice consistency and speed.
Builders/educators who ship prompts to teammates, students, or API endpoint=
s and need guard-rails that survive hand-offs.
Up front, a confession: leaving those boxes blank is often the smartest mov=
e. If your work swings wildly from legal disclaimers to movie recommendatio=
ns, hard-coded defaults can do more harm than good=E2=80=94consuming tokens=
, leaking jargon into casual chats, and aging into silent bugs. The payoff =
only appears when your workflow is both high-frequency and stable (think: w=
eekly release notes, daily customer replies, recurring grant abstracts).
Look here are some blank boxes=E2=80=A6
The rest of this article walks you through the instruction stack that gover=
ns ChatGPT, a decision grid for picking between giant task-specific prompts=
 and evergreen Custom Instructions, concrete role-based templates, and quic=
k tactics to prevent a PRD style guide from hijacking your Friday-night fil=
m debate. By the end you=E2=80=99ll know exactly what belongs in those boxe=
s=E2=80=94and just as importantly, what doesn=E2=80=99t.
First=E2=80=94How ChatGPT=E2=80=99s Instruction Stack Actually Works
Before you decide whether to shoe-horn a style guide into Custom Instructio=
ns or leave the boxes empty, you need to see the plumbing. Every request yo=
u send to ChatGPT is really a bundle of five instruction layers, passed to =
the model in strict top-down order:
Policy  (global, immutable)
=E2=94=94=E2=94=80 System message  (GPT builder or API)
   =E2=94=94=E2=94=80 Custom Instructions  (your two-box panel)
      =E2=94=94=E2=94=80 Developer message  (optional in GPT/API)
         =E2=94=94=E2=94=80 User prompt  (what you type)
1. Policy =E2=80=93 the invisible ceiling
OpenAI=E2=80=99s content and safety rules ride above everything else. You c=
an=E2=80=99t read them in full, you can=E2=80=99t override them, and they w=
ill nullify any downstream request that conflicts. Think of Policy as the e=
lectrical code in your city: every design decision you make must fit inside=
 it, whether you=E2=80=99ve read the handbook or not.
2. System message =E2=80=93 the voice of the app, not the user
When you open a public Custom GPT or an app that calls the OpenAI API, a Sy=
stem message is injected before your chat even starts. It defines the assis=
tant=E2=80=99s identity (=E2=80=9CYou are a math tutor=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D) a=
nd tool permissions. Because it sits just below Policy, it outranks anythin=
g you write later=E2=80=94including your personal Custom Instructions. If a=
 System line says =E2=80=9CRespond only in French,=E2=80=9D every English p=
hrase you add in the two boxes becomes a polite suggestion, not a command.
3. Custom Instructions =E2=80=93 your sticky defaults
These are the two panels you can edit in ChatGPT=E2=80=99s settings. They f=
ire on every conversation you start while you=E2=80=99re signed-in. Crucial=
ly, they also consume tokens on every turn: 500 characters in each box equa=
ls roughly 100 tokens, which lowers the working memory available for long s=
ource docs and, in metered API land, costs real money. They are perfect for=
 evergreen, low-risk rules (tone, empathy framework, disclaimers) and dange=
rous for volatile or mutually exclusive ones.
4. Developer message =E2=80=93 a scoped override
If you share a Custom GPT or build a SaaS feature on the API, you can slip =
an extra =E2=80=9Cdeveloper=E2=80=9D layer beneath the user=E2=80=99s login=
=2E It inherits your Custom Instruction=
s but outranks the user prompt. That l=
ets you freeze behaviour for end-users (=E2=80=9CAlways cite sources=E2=80=
=9D) without forcing the rule on yourself in other chats.
5. User prompt =E2=80=93 the moment-to-moment ask
Everything you type in the chat window lands at the bottom of the stack. It=
=E2=80=99s the most specific instruction but also the weakest: any contradi=
ction with the four layers above is automatically resolved in favour of the=
 higher layer. That=E2=80=99s why the assistant sometimes seems to ignore y=
ou=E2=80=94because it is obeying something you can=E2=80=99t see.
Precedence in action
Suppose your Custom Instructions demand =E2=80=9Cno emojis,=E2=80=9D but a =
public Custom GPT you open has a System line, =E2=80=9CRespond with a frien=
dly emoji at the end of each paragraph =F0=9F=98=8A.=E2=80=9D Emojis win (a=
nd btw I hated the emoji update). And yep, if you blank out your boxes and =
instead paste =E2=80=9Cnever use emojis=E2=80=9D inside the user prompt eac=
h time, the GPT still sprinkles smiles=E2=80=94System beats User.
The token-budget reality
All five layers are concatenated into a single prompt fed to the model. Eve=
ry extra line shrinks the remaining space for your source text. That=E2=80=
=99s why the decision to preload defaults should come before you fuss over =
wording: sometimes the cheapest, safest move is to start with empty boxes a=
nd let each task carry its own context.
With the hierarchy=E2=80=94and its trade-offs=E2=80=94clear, we can now tac=
kle the practical question: when do Custom Instructions save time, and when=
 do they create hidden debt? The next section walks through a simple decisi=
on grid that answers exactly that.
Next =E2=80=94 Decide First: Default, Giant Prompt, or Custom Instructions?
You now know where Custom Instructions sit in the stack. The next step is t=
o decide whether they=E2=80=99re the right tool at all for the work you put=
 through ChatGPT. Two factors dominate this call:
Frequency =E2=80=93 How often you repeat the same deliverable pattern.
Volatility =E2=80=93 How often the rules for that deliverable change (or cl=
ash with other tasks you do).
Put them on a 2 =C3=97 2 grid and the best strategy falls out:
The two-question litmus test
Will the rule ever be wrong for another task I run from this account?
Yes =E2=86=92 keep it out of Custom Instructions.
Does this deliverable represent more than ~50 % of my ChatGPT usage this mo=
nth?
Yes =E2=86=92 consider Custom Instructions; No =E2=86=92 stick with a reusa=
ble task-prompt.
If you answer =E2=80=9Cno=E2=80=9D to both, the safest, cheapest path is a =
blank panel and a purpose-built prompt whenever you need it.
Quick examples
Content marketer drafting five LinkedIn posts a day in the same brand voice=
: High-Frequency/Low-Volatility =E2=86=92 Custom Instructions pay off.
Product manager who flips between PRDs, roadmap debates, and personal movie=
 picks: High-Frequency/High-Volatility =E2=86=92 keep brand rules in a gian=
t PRD prompt and leave the boxes empty.
Founder polishing a seed-round pitch once: Low-Frequency/High-Volatility =
